english:
  title: 'A Prayer for Rain: Blue Words Recited at the Sogyeokjeon Ritual'
  author: Byeon Gye-ryang
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Human affairs move below; heavenly changes respond above. The principle of heaven and earth in resonance—how manifest it is! I, lacking virtue and shallow of understanding, have inherited the silent blessing of Heaven above and the great foundation laid by the Progenitor King. For many years now, I have harbored the hope of bringing even modest peace to the realm. Yet now, in this season of flourishing fields, drought's calamity has come upon us. Reflecting deeply on its cause, I dare not rest easy. How could I seek the fault elsewhere? I must turn my blame inward.

    I elevated four brothers of the Min clan—relatives of the royal consort—to the highest offices, granting them honor and prosperity. Yet they proved ungrateful. Their hearts proved disloyal; they harbored treacherous doubts and nursed the heart of beasts, conspiring to extinguish my bloodline. Their treachery has long been evident, yet I could not bring myself to act swiftly. For seven years I have endured, veiling their crimes in silence. At that time, the anguish in my heart—Heaven itself knows it. Since they had gravely offended the royal ancestral shrine and the state altars, I could not grant them endless forgiveness. Thus they were commanded to meet their own end. This decision I made for the sake of the ancestral shrine and the state, and for the righteousness between ruler and subject.

    Yet I know not whether it truly accords with the Will of the Supreme Lord. Similarly, among the meritorious ministers, some have been punished, others pardoned—all because their hearts were not loyal, their treachery laid bare. They brought this upon themselves, not through any hatred I harbored, but through their own deeds. Yet even here, I cannot be certain whether it aligns with Heaven's judgment.

    As for the construction projects: these were undertaken because this capital was founded by the Progenitor King, yet the royal halls and connecting galleries remained incomplete. There was no proper place for scholars to dwell, no shelter for workers. Thus these works became necessary. Yet how could such undertakings proceed without burdening the people? For these various causes, I have earned Heaven's displeasure.

    Now, chastened by this warning, I tremble in fear and dread. I dare lay bare my failings before the Highest, knowing my words may offend. Alas! Because of my one person, billions of my subjects suffer first. Even the winged, the aquatic, the moving creatures, and growing things have all lost their sustenance. To speak of this grieves my heart deeply.

    I look up to the vast Heaven; I beseech its compassionate understanding. Grant forgiveness for my transgressions, wash away my sins. Let rain and sunshine come in their seasons; let the hundred grains flourish. May every household have sufficiency and every person find plenty. May the people rest in peace and all things abound. This is my deepest prayer, without end.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Sogyeokjeon (昭格殿) was a royal shrine dedicated to receiving divine communications and performing rain-prayer rituals.
  - key: ''
    value: The Min clan brothers' treachery refers to the Minsaennim Incident, a historical event where powerful court relatives were executed for disloyalty.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'blue words' (청사/靑詞) refer to ceremonial prayers written on blue or azure-colored paper, used in Daoist and shamanistic rituals.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Progenitor King' (太祖) refers to the founder of the Joseon Dynasty, Taejo.
